auth_1: Kim, Jae Yeon; Ng, Margaret
doi_1: forthcoming so no DOI is available at this point
opend_ended: In so many ways. After SICSS, I became a senior data science fellow at D-Lab and UC Berkeley. Then, I began to get involved in a project that used big data and machine learning to map civil society in the US at the SNF Agora Institute at Johns Hopkins. I was a predoc and have been a postdoc at the same institute. I published one pedagogy article and another article on professionalization is soon to be submitted. I've taught many courses and workshops on computational methods and put them together as an open-access textbook. I've started three research projects with the people I've met through SICSS.

name: Jaren Haber
proj_1: Digitizing Segregation: How Charter School Websites Signal Race- and Class-Specific Educational Ideologies
auth_1: Jaren R. Haber, Nicholas Camp, and Jae Yeon Kim
opend_ended: Participating in SICSS was one of the most engaging and rewarding experiences of my professional career thus far. The technical training, open discussion, and opportunity to push the envelope of how we think about computational methods through collaboration solidified my identity and allowed me to confidently serve as a "computational social scientist". Highlights included learning about GovLab, applying Structural Topic Models, talking about the ethics of web-scraping, and seeding ongoing research into digital segregation through school websites. I felt so grateful for the opportunity and convinced of its utility that I helped organize the first SICSS in the San Francisco Bay Area in 2020. This is essential work and I think must continue. Thanks for reading and supporting SICSS!
